## 1 Overview
In this lesson you will learn how to connect multiple shift registers to the development board. The big advantage is that we do not use any supplimentary pins for the second shift register, we only have to connect the dataPin of the second shift register to QH' pin of the first shift register.

## 3 Connections
Below, you can find the schematic:
Below, you can find a visual representation of the connections:

## 4 Code

The code is very similar with the one from the previous lesson. The only
difference is that the two LEDs connected to the development board in the previous
lesson, we will connect them to the second shift register.

The code starts by including the libraries used and declaring the pins used by
the shift registers. These pins will be set as OUTPUT and then initialized with 0.

With a couple of modifications, our **shift()** function can work now with 16
bit variables. We only needed to change the range of the for loop and now can run
thru all bits and the condition is also changed. Because we are starting from the MSB,
and if we have 0b0000000000000001, the first iteration is: **0b1000000000000000 &
(buffer << 0)) = 0b1000000000000000 & 0b0000000000000001 = 0**. The second is:
**0b1000000000000000 & (buffer << 1)) = 0b1000000000000000 &
0b0000000000000010 = 0**.

The first function will turn on each LED at an interval of 1 s. This function is
similar with the one from the previous lesson, but this time we are working with two
shift registers so we have a 16 bit variable and our range for the for loop will be from
0 to 10 (10 LEDs).

The charging effect is similar with the one form the previous lesson, but this
time we will use an array that stores ten 16 bits values.

Another function created in this code is another_effect() and in this
function we have a 16 bits array with 9 values and, using a for loop, we will send
these values to the shift registers.

The last effect created is the one that will turn on the LEDs like a barcode.
This function contains an array with three values and in the for loop, that will repeat
10 times, we will play them one after another.

These functions will be called in the while True loop and an effect will play
every 0.5 s.

"""
 * Credits: www.plusivo.com
 *
 * Lesson 28: Multiple Shift Registers
 *
 * The code below is created for the lesson "Multiple Shift Registers",
 * where you will learn how to use multiple shift registers
 * and using only three pins from the development board.
 *
 * In this example we are using two shift registers, but you can
 * connect multiple shift registers and obtain "infinite"
 * pins on your development board.
 *
 * More details can be found in the guide.
 *
"""

#we import the RPi.GPIO library with the name of GPIO
import RPi.GPIO as GPIO
import time

GPIO.setmode(GPIO.BOARD)

#declare the pins used by the shift registers
dataPin = 12
latchPin = 10
clockPin = 8

#set all the pins as OUTPUT
GPIO.setup(dataPin, GPIO.OUT)
GPIO.setup(latchPin, GPIO.OUT)
GPIO.setup(clockPin, GPIO.OUT)

#set the initial state for the pins as LOW
GPIO.output(dataPin, GPIO.LOW)
GPIO.output(latchPin, GPIO.LOW)
GPIO.output(clockPin, GPIO.LOW)

def shift(buffer):
        #send the bits to the shift registers
    for i in range(0,16):
        GPIO.output(dataPin, (0b1000000000000000 & (buffer << i)))
        GPIO.output(clockPin, GPIO.HIGH)
        time.sleep(0.001)
        GPIO.output(clockPin, GPIO.LOW)

        #shift the bits
    GPIO.output(latchPin, GPIO.HIGH)
    time.sleep(0.001)
    GPIO.output(latchPin, GPIO.LOW)


def individual():
      #declare a 16 bit variable with the most
      #significant bit set to HIGH
      led = 0b0000000000000001

          #turn on each led of the Ledbar
      for i in range(0,10):
          shift(led)
          led = led << 1
          time.sleep(1)

      #set the shift registers to output 0
      shift(0)

def charging():
    #declare a 16 bit array to store the states for the
    #10 LEDs connected to the shift registers
    charging_array =   [0b0000000000000001,
                        0b0000000000000011,
                        0b0000000000000111,
                        0b0000000000001111,
                        0b0000000000011111,
                        0b0000000000111111,
                        0b0000000001111111,
                        0b0000000011111111,
                        0b0000000111111111,
                        0b0000001111111111]

        #send each element of the array to the shift registers
    for i in range(0,10):
        shift(charging_array[i])
        time.sleep(0.5)

    #tun off the LEDs
    shift(0)


def another_effect():
    #declare a 16 bit array to store the states for the
    #10 LEDs connected to the shift registers
    effect =   [0b0000001000000001,
                0b0000000100000010,
                0b0000000010000100,
                0b0000000001001000,
                0b0000000000110000,
                0b0000000001001000,
                0b0000000010000100,
                0b0000000100000010,
                0b0000001000000001]

        #send each element of the array to the shift registers
    for i in range(0,9):
        shift(effect[i])
        time.sleep(0.5)

    #tun off the LEDs
    shift(0)

def barcode():
    #declare a 16 bit array to store the states for the
    #10 LEDs connected to the shift registers
    barcode_array =    [0b0000001001001001,
                        0b0000000100100100,
                        0b0000000010010010]

        #send each element of the array to the shift registers
    for i in range(0,10):
        shift(barcode_array[0])
        time.sleep(0.2)

        shift(barcode_array[1])
        time.sleep(0.2)

        shift(barcode_array[2])
        time.sleep(0.2)

    #tun off the LEDs
    shift(0)

try:
        while True:
                #turn on each LED and wait 1 s
                individual()

                #wait 500 ms before the next effect
                time.sleep(0.5)

                #turn on the Ledbar and show a charging effect
                charging()

                #wait 500 ms
                time.sleep(0.5)

                another_effect()

                #wait 500 ms
                time.sleep(0.5)

                barcode()

                #wait 500 ms
                time.sleep(0.5)

except KeyboardInterrupt:
        pass

shift(0)
GPIO.cleanup()
